data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically on .NET 8 and require no migration.

That said, the code would benefit from modernization using `Task` or `Parallel.ForEach`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            Thread.Sleep(100);
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

This is simpler, uses the thread pool efficiently, and avoids the classic closure-over-loop-variable bug in your original `foreach` (where `item` could be captured by reference and change before the thread runs).

**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**
